We are given a graph structure representing N nodes which are on a network , 
our job is to find the maximum time taken for a signal sent from one node to reach all the nodes.
We need the shortest time for the signal to reach every node.
So this is a shortest path problem.
Because edges have positive weights, we usually solve it using:
Dijkstra’s Algorithm


Algorithm: Dijkstra’s Algorithm
We use Dijkstra because we need the minimum time for the signal to reach every node from starting node k.
Steps:
Build a graph using adjacency list.
For each edge [u, v, w], store:
u -> v with time w
Create a distances array.
distances[i] means the shortest time to reach node i.
Initially, all are infinity.
distances[k] = 0 because signal starts from k.
Use a Min Heap / Priority Queue.
It always gives the node with the smallest current distance.
While the priority queue is not empty:
Take the node with the smallest distance.
Visit its neighbors.
If going through this node gives a shorter path, update the distance.
After processing:
If any node is still infinity, return -1.
Otherwise, return the maximum value from distances.
Because the answer is when the last node receives the signal



code:
class Solution {
    public int networkDelayTime(int[][] times, int n, int k) {

        // Step 1: Build graph
        // graph key = source node
        // graph value = list of {target node, travel time}
        Map<Integer, List<int[]>> graph = new HashMap<>();

        for (int[] edge : times) {
            int source = edge[0];
            int target = edge[1];
            int time = edge[2];

            graph
                .computeIfAbsent(source, x -> new ArrayList<>())
                .add(new int[]{target, time});
        }

        // Step 2: Min heap based on distance/time
        // Each element is {node, current shortest distance}
        PriorityQueue<int[]> pq = new PriorityQueue<>(
            Comparator.comparingInt(a -> a[1])
        );

        // Start from node k with distance 0
        pq.offer(new int[]{k, 0});

        // Step 3: distances[i] stores shortest time to reach node i
        int[] distances = new int[n + 1];

        // Initially, every node is unreachable
        Arrays.fill(distances, Integer.MAX_VALUE);

        // Distance from k to itself is 0
        distances[k] = 0;

        // Step 4: Dijkstra's algorithm
        while (!pq.isEmpty()) {

            int[] current = pq.poll();

            int currentNode = current[0];
            int currentDist = current[1];

            // If this is an old longer distance, skip it
            if (currentDist > distances[currentNode]) {
                continue;
            }

            // If current node has neighbors, check them
            if (graph.containsKey(currentNode)) {

                for (int[] neighbor : graph.get(currentNode)) {

                    int nextNode = neighbor[0];
                    int travelTime = neighbor[1];

                    // New distance to reach nextNode through currentNode
                    int nextDist = currentDist + travelTime;

                    // If we found a shorter path, update it
                    if (nextDist < distances[nextNode]) {
                        distances[nextNode] = nextDist;

                        // Add updated node and distance to min heap
                        pq.offer(new int[]{nextNode, nextDist});
                    }
                }
            }
        }

        // Step 5: Find the maximum shortest distance
        // Skip index 0 because nodes are labeled from 1 to n
        int maxDist = Arrays.stream(distances)
                            .skip(1)
                            .max()
                            .getAsInt();

        // If any node is unreachable, maxDist will still be Integer.MAX_VALUE
        if (maxDist == Integer.MAX_VALUE) {
            return -1;
        }

        // Otherwise, return the time when the last node receives the signal
        return maxDist;
    }
}
